Europe Needs Immigration to Restart
Brussels—More than 900 migrants attempting to reach Europe have drowned in the Mediterranean this year.
Meanwhile, the rescue ships Open Arms and Ocean Viking have been searching all summer for safe harbors where the passengers on board could disembark.
Refugee and migrant camps on the Greek island of Lesbos are overcrowded, and other安置 camps in Libya are in similarly poor conditions.
Turkey has torn up the 2016 agreement to prevent migrants from entering the EU.
Despite Europe's desire to help migrants and its respect for international law, it does not want to be overcrowded.
In 2015–16, the number of refugees and migrants entering the EU surged—many of them fleeing the war in Syria—which greatly affected trust within the EU.
The massive influx of migrants eroded confidence in government management of the EU's external borders and asylum policies, also highlighting that cooperation with countries of origin is largely ineffective.
Therefore, migration has become a political football, a favorite issue for populists.
Under the leadership of President Ursula von der Leyen, the new European Commission must regain control of the migration issue while respecting the dignity of those seeking a better life.
Therefore, the EU needs to reestablish guidelines in four areas to mobilize member states to act in Europe's interest.
First, the EU must urgently secure its external borders, a prerequisite for keeping its internal borders open.
Countries where people can freely move internally, including the United States, India, China, Switzerland, and Russia, do not outsource external border control to a particular state or region.
Controlling the EU's external borders is both a collective task and a national responsibility.
Frontex, the EU's border and coast guard agency, must be further strengthened and should deploy joint security forces with member states — including along coastlines and at airports.
The EU must also restart Operation Sophia to combat illegal migration in the Mediterranean.
Second, Europe needs to handle economic migrants and asylum seekers separately.
Treating them as one has brought the asylum system close to collapse; handling them separately helps ensure that migrants concerned about their safety can voice their concerns with their rights protected.
Addressing the EU's real economic and social needs requires effective blue or green card policies targeting economic migrants and the implementation of overall immigration targets.
This cannot be left to the next migration crisis before considering the introduction of these mechanisms.
To achieve this, the EU must break the taboo.
First, the number of economic migrants entering the EU labor market must be recognized as a matter of common interest.
Second, policies must clearly define which migrants are welcome.
Third, member states must identify what EU assistance is needed to ensure a smooth immigration process.
Finally, visas and work permits must be brought to the forefront to facilitate the return of illegal immigrants to their countries of origin.
Indeed, according to the EU treaties, member states need to manage immigrants coming from outside the EU themselves.
However, if governments reach agreement on overall EU immigration targets, it would be a significant step forward.
In return, member states can specify the countries of origin and specific requirements for economic migrants they wish to admit, as well as the EU budget resources needed to accommodate them.
In this way, the right to accept migrants would become a privilege rather than a burden.
For example, Canada has long implemented an active immigration policy, selecting immigrants based on criteria such as country of origin, skill level, and age.
Europe can do the same.
Third, the EU needs to improve its asylum system.
First, the one-size-fits-all requirement for compulsory distribution of asylum seekers within the EU must be abandoned.
This requirement has undermined the atmosphere within the EU, but it could still be feasible if border, asylum, and immigration systems are fully effective.
Moreover, it is not feasible to expect frontline EU member states to tackle the issue of illegal migrants crossing external borders on their own.
The camps are overcrowded, and migrants are subjected to abuse by authorities or driven northward.
The responsibility of the first EU member state where migrants arrive must be reinforced by EU solidarity.
The EU must also provide experts and funding to streamline the operations and management capabilities of national asylum agencies.
Only in this way can national decisions be respected throughout the Schengen area, ensuring the integrity of the cross-border travel zone.
Once the operations and management capabilities of national asylum agencies are streamlined, the asylum application process can also be shared among member states.
Fourth, the EU should establish stronger mutually beneficial cooperation with countries of origin and transit countries.
These connections are crucial for repatriating migrants who are legally prohibited from entering the EU to their countries of origin.
To ensure cooperation, the EU should mobilize all diplomatic policy tools, including development aid and investment funds, as well as programs in areas such as security, trade, energy, agriculture, fisheries, climate action, aviation, and health.
EU immigration targets, as well as skill cooperation aimed at preparing jobs in Europe, can be offered to third countries eager for stable remittances.
At the same time, the EU must address the root causes of migration.
This includes the population explosion in sub-Saharan Africa; climate change affecting food security; outbreaks of infectious diseases; ethnic conflicts; and a lack of job opportunities.
The EU's aid should focus on rebuilding stability and reducing risks through support for security, community resilience, and good governance.
Success in this area can make investments safer, unlock private and domestic financing, thereby achieving national economic growth, job creation, and provide alternatives to migration.
The new European Commission has the opportunity to move the EU away from instinctive reactions to the migration crisis and toward a more coherent and sustained approach, whether internally or externally.
We must not miss this opportunity.
